{"key":"processedPost-16941468","value":{"id":16941468,"first":16938037,"last":16941593,"when":1349061954,"utime":"10/01/12 06:25 AM","content":"Mycelium rips through coir because it's an excellent bulk substrate material.&nbsp; Coir has few nutes plants use thus it makes a great hydroponic medium.&nbsp; However, mycelium breaks down solids at the cellular level, and coir has lots of cell structure for mycelium to feed on.&nbsp; I've spawned bulk to coir/verm and plain coir and performance is similar to horse manure or straw.<br /><br />Coir also performs well after sterilizing because the heat cooks it, making it easier for the mycelium to digest.&nbsp; Sterilizing bulk substrates such as manure can lead to a higher incidence of contaminants, but not so with coir.<br />RR","title":"Re: should i soak my peat moss/hay casing overnight in water?"}}